        <title>STARTING MOTORS</title>
        <apply>
            <configure>
                <vendorgroup/>

                <vendor>DELCO-REMY</vendor>
                <truckmodelgroup/>

                <truckmodel>2000</truckmodel>
                <truckmodel>3000</truckmodel>
                <truckmodel>4000</truckmodel>
                <truckmodel>5000</truckmodel>
                <truckmodel>7000</truckmodel>
                <truckmodel>8100</truckmodel>
                <truckmodel>8200</truckmodel>
                <truckmodel>8300</truckmodel>
                <truckmodel>9100</truckmodel>
                <truckmodel>9200</truckmodel>
                <truckmodel>9300</truckmodel>
                <truckmodel>9400</truckmodel>
                <truckmodel>9600</truckmodel>
                <truckmodel>9700</truckmodel>
                <truckmodel>9800</truckmodel>
                <vendcodegroup/>

                <vendcode>37-MT</vendcode>
                <vendcode>42-MT</vendcode>
                <vendcode>50-MT</vendcode>
            </configure>
        </apply>
        <description>
            <geninfo>
                <lev1>
                    <para>Heavy duty cranking motors (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f0803601">Figure 1</hotlnk>,
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f0803602">Figure 2</hotlnk>, and
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f0803603">Figure 3</hotlnk>) have a shift lever solenoid plunger that are
                        totally enclosed to protect them from exposure to dirt, icing conditions and splash. The nose
                        housing can be rotated to obtain a number of different solenoid positions with respect to the
                        mounting flange. Also, the commutator end cap can be removed to inspect the brushes.
                    </para>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <figure id="f0803601" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g0803601" filename="../figg08/G0803601.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Typical 37-MT Motor, 42-MT Is Similar</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>1. SOLENOID</callout1>
                            <callout1>2. LEVER HOUSING</callout1>
                            <callout1>3. NOSE HOUSING</callout1>
                            <callout1>4. FIELD FRAME</callout1>
                            <callout1>5. END CAP</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <figure id="f0803602" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g0803602" filename="../figg08/G0803602.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>End View of 42-MT Motor Showing Thermostat Connector</caption>
                    </figure>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <figure id="f0803603" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g0803603" filename="../figg08/G0803603.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Typical 50-MT Motor</caption>
                    </figure>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <para>Lubrication is provided in the sintered bronze bushings by an oil saturated wick. Oil can be
                        added to each wick by removing an oil reservoir cup which is accessible on the outside of the
                        motor. Additional information on lubrication is provided in
                        <hotlnk document="s08036_HL0803601.xml" xrefid="hl0803601">LUBRICATION</hotlnk>.
                    </para>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <para>The pinion is moved into mesh with the ring gear by the action of the solenoid. The pinion
                        remains engaged until the solenoid circuit is interrupted. In the case of a butt engagement on
                        42-MT and 50-MT, damage to the pinion and gear teeth is prevented by not energizing.
                    </para>
                </lev1>
            </geninfo>
        </description>
